postcontent: For sale or trade is a G33/40 Mountain Carbine.  The G33/40 carbine was issued to German Gebirgstruppen Mountain Infantry units during WWII. All G33/40 rifles were produced between 1940 and 1942 at Brno in Czechoslovakia. This rifle's receiver is  stamped with the "dot" code, and dated 1942.   This rifle has been sporterized (non-original stock).  The action is the "small ring" version and is desirable for building custom rifles.  Not sure what it's worth.  Actions can go for $5-600 and barrels $1-300.  The rifle has the original rear sight and front sight but not the front sight cover.  I am asking $850 but would be willing to entertain other offers or trades.  Don't be shy.

title: For Sale:  HELL FIRE Trigger System
postcontent:
The Hellfire trigger system is a small metal piece that attaches to the trigger behind the trigger of your semi-automatic rifle or pistol. 

It has a "finger" that presses against the back of your trigger and this pressure is adjustable.

The effect is to increase the force to return your trigger to the forward position.

Which means the Hellfire system allows you to shoot your gun at "full-auto" rates even though you are still pulling the trigger each time a round is discharged. 
New never used took out of packge for picture      local  pickup  Monroe

postcontent:
This is considered to be one of the best CCW revolvers ever made, and the only reason I’m considering parting with it is because I am consolidating calibers and funding another purchase.

This is a 4th Generation Charter Arms “PUG” from the plant in Shelton, Connecticut, and is the best model they’ve ever designed. The alloy frame keeps it light, the 2" barrel keeps it pocketable, and the .44 Special cartridge packs the punch of a .45 ACP with far less recoil than a .357 Magnum. Magnum recoil is very sharp and snappy, whereas the .44 Special is more like a firm push. This is the best big bore caliber for short barrels or recoil sensitive shooters, and is a very accurate round.

The PUG has a stainless finish, practical sights, and a snag-free DAO hammer. Lockup is very tight and revolver has a VERY low round count. It is practically in like new condition.

There is exactly 120 rounds of defense ammo (80 rds Gold Dot, 20 rds Silvertip) and a couple of loose Remington lead flat tips.  I can also throw in a cheapo IWB holster to complete the package.

In 1983, the LUSA-A2 SMG was developed by INDEP Industries of Portugal who, at the time, was manufacturing under license from H&K, the HK21 and the HK G3. Improvements and modifications were a continuing process, culminating in 1992, and with a development cost of 2.5 million dollars. The weapons are now used by the Portuguese and three other European countries.

The Name LUSA is derived from Lusitania, which is present day Portugal. Although designed as a military weapon, the LUSA-A2 is well-suited for law enforcement. The trigger group is nearly identical to that of the H&K MP-5 and the barrel is quick-change, similar to the UZI. The bolt and carrier are one unit.

In 2004, INDEP sold all dies, tooling, fixtures and manufacturing rights to group of well established names in the firearms industry. Stan Andrewski, owner of Stan's Gunsmithing for over 30 years in New Hampshire, Jerry Prasser, owner of Recon Ordnance for 29 years in Wisconsin, and Ralph Demicco, owner of Riley's Gun Shop. The company was named LUSA USA.

title: For Sale/Trade:  German 9mm Makarov - 9X18, 2 Mags, Holster, Ammo - Very Nice
postcontent:
Up for sale or trade is my "safe queen" German Makarov 9/18. I've owned it for over 20 years and fired exactly 92 rounds through it. It comes with two magazines, the leather holster, two set of grips (OEM brown plastic and Pierce rubber) and an optional two 50-rd boxes of FMJ ammo. When I purchased it I paid extra to the distributor for special hand select. With only very slight bluing wear at the muzzle and safety, I estimate this gun to be 98%.

This is a rare pistol as it has a fixed rear sight. Only a small amount were imported before importation was cut off. Only pistols with a very cheap, low quality adjustable rear sights were allowed to be imported afterward. This one is the real deal. The bore is chrome lined an excellent and the inside of the slide and frame shows little to no wear. The letter code shows this pistol was made in 1960.

From the web: East Germany
The Ernst Thaelman factory in Suhl, Thueringen made what are considered by some to be the finest pre-fall-of-the-Berlin Wall Makarovs. The finish is nice, the fit and machining is of quality you'd expect from a German shop, and they shoot like a dream. Almost all that came into this country had already seen service, so their quality varies by how they were treated by the person who carried them. Nonetheless, most have more holster wear than bore wear. They occasionally still pop up at dealers and at gun shows.

If you check Gunbroker.com right now, you'll find one just like mine already with one bid at $550 before shipping, not to mention the dealer fees for NICS after
you get it here. So my price is firm at $495 for the pistol alone or $545 with the two boxes of ammo. But..	I will entertain trades up or down, so let me know
what you have. No offense intended, but no response means no interest. And I can send larger pics if desired. Thanks for looking.
